Transfer matrix modelling was done to simulate the operation of the electroabsorption modulators. The modelling procedure followed that outlined by Ziffer et al.41 Layer thicknesses were set to their experimentally determined values, and the optical constants for the glass, ITO, and perovskites were those found through ellipsometry measurements. The optical constants for Al2O3, ZrO2, TiO2, PMMA, sputtered SiO2, and Ag were taken from the literature78–82. The angle of incidence was set to 45°. Reflectance spectra were calculated for the case of an absent field, and for a field present with Δn and Δk added to the optical constants for the perovskite layer. Δn and Δk were calculated from the differential forms of the relations εr = n2 − k2 and εi = 2nk. As Ziffer et al. have provided, the following equations were used:13Δn=Δεik+Δεrn2n2+k2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
