				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\sqrt {\left\langle {\psi _2\psi _1\left| {\left( {r - r\prime } \right)^2} \right|\psi _1\psi _2} \right\rangle }$$\end{document} on a 3D grid88. Atomic illustrations were produced by the VESTA software89.

Calculations of the well width dependence were done with an infinite well potential subjected to an electric field. The wavefunctions for such a potential are Airy functions. These calculations are only quantitative for a known effective well width, as the actual well width does not account for penetration of the wavefunctions into the finite barriers of real materials. The energetic shifts in the quantum regime exactly match the theoretical relation given by,16ΔE=m*e2F2L424ℏ2π21-15π2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
